+# Preprocessing leakage audit
+
+## Findings
+
+- **Imputation:** no leakage in the main pipeline. `apply_missing_value_pipeline` computes missing-value drop decisions and median imputation values from `X_train` only, then applies the learned columns/medians to `X_test`.
+- **Scaling:** no leakage in model fitting. Neural-network and scikit-learn model helpers fit `StandardScaler` on the fitting/training rows and only call `transform` on validation/test rows.
+- **Feature selection:** leakage existed in the interactive backward/forward selection routines. They repeatedly called the normal test-evaluation path (`repeat_fit_model`) for each candidate feature subset, which means the held-out test split influenced which subset was selected. That turns the test split into a model-selection validation split and makes the later reported test score optimistic.
+- **Target encoding:** no target encoder is implemented in the audited training code. Categorical handling found in feature-importance reporting uses one-hot encoding (`pd.get_dummies`), not target/mean encoding.
+
+## Correction
+
+Feature-selection candidate subsets now use an inner train/validation split carved only from the existing training partition. The saved test partition returned by `read_prep_data` is intentionally ignored during subset scoring and remains reserved for final model evaluation.
+
+Expected impact: feature selection may choose a different subset, and final test R² may decrease because the test set is no longer reused during subset selection. This decrease is desirable: it is a less biased estimate of generalization performance. Training/validation scores during selection may also have higher variance because they are estimated from fewer rows than the former train/test evaluation path.
